    question: "An organization outsources its entire IT function to a managed service provider (MSP). The service level agreement (SLA) specifies 99.9% uptime for the financial reporting system. The auditor discovers that actual uptime was 97.2% over the past year, resulting in approximately 245 hours of downtime. The organization did not invoke the SLA penalty provisions and did not monitor service levels during the year. What governance issue exists?",
    options: ["97.2% uptime is acceptable for financial systems","Failure to monitor SLA compliance and enforce contractual provisions indicates a breakdown in vendor governance — the organization cannot demonstrate effective oversight of a critical outsourced function, and 245 hours of financial system downtime may have impacted reporting timeliness","SLA monitoring is the vendor's responsibility, not the organization's","Penalty provisions should never be invoked to maintain a good relationship with the MSP"],
