    question: "A Content Delivery Network (CDN) improves application performance by:",
    options: ["Deleting old content automatically","Distributing content across geographically dispersed edge servers — serving users from the nearest server to reduce latency, improve load times, and provide protection against DDoS attacks through traffic distribution","Compressing all files to the smallest possible size","Limiting the number of users who can access an application"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "CDN benefits: (1) Performance — serve static content (images, CSS, JavaScript, videos) from edge servers closest to users, reducing latency and improving page load times, (2) Scalability — handle traffic spikes without overloading origin servers, (3) Availability — if one edge server fails, traffic is automatically routed to the next closest server, (4) DDoS protection — large CDN networks can absorb volumetric DDoS attacks by distributing traffic across many edge servers, (5) SSL/TLS termination — CDN handles encryption/decryption at the edge, reducing origin server load. Major CDN providers: Cloudflare, Akamai, AWS CloudFront, Azure CDN. Security considerations: (1) SSL/TLS certificate management, (2) Cache poisoning prevention, (3) Origin server protection (restrict direct access), (4) DDoS mitigation features. CPA relevance: CDN reliability affects availability of web-based financial applications (customer portals, investor relations, online banking).",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - CDNs don't automatically delete old content; content expiration is typically managed through cache control headers or manual purging.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - CDNs store content on servers geographically closer to users, reducing the distance data travels, which significantly lowers latency and improves loading speeds. This distributed architecture also helps absorb and mitigate Distributed Denial-of-Service (DDoS) attacks by spreading the malicious traffic across numerous servers.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - While CDNs may support compression, their primary function isn't to compress all files; compression is usually handled separately and then cached by the CDN.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - CDNs are designed to improve accessibility and performance for all users, not to limit the number of users who can access an application.",
    },
    educational: "A Content Delivery Network (CDN) acts like a global network of caches for your website's static assets. Think of it as having copies of your website's images, videos, and other files stored closer to users around the world, resulting in faster loading times and a better user experience. This also reduces the load on your main server, improving its overall performance and resilience.",
    examTip: "When you see 'latency' or 'page load times' in a question about improving web application performance, think CDN.",
    memoryAid: "CDN = Content Distributed Near(by)",
    reference: "NIST; CDN Architecture",
