    difficulty: "hard",
    skillLevel: "Analysis",
    question: "Recovery Point Objective (RPO) determines:",
    options: ["Number of recovery personnel","How long recovery takes","The maximum acceptable data loss measured in time (backup frequency)","Cost of recovery"],
    correctAnswer: 2,
    explanation: "RPO: max acceptable data loss (time since last backup). 1-hour RPO = hourly backups. RTO: max acceptable downtime (time to restore operations). Together they drive backup/recovery strategy and costs.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - The number of recovery personnel is determined by factors like the complexity of the systems and the size of the IT team, not directly by the RPO.",
      1: "Why option B is WRONG - How long recovery takes is determined by the Recovery Time Objective (RTO), which is distinct from the RPO.",
      2: "Why option C is CORRECT - The Recovery Point Objective (RPO) defines the maximum tolerable period in which data might be lost from an IT service due to a major incident. It essentially dictates how frequently backups must be performed.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - The cost of recovery is influenced by both RPO and RTO, as well as factors like infrastructure and personnel, but RPO alone does not determine the total cost.",
    },
    educational: "RPO and RTO are critical components of a business continuity and disaster recovery plan. RPO focuses on data loss, while RTO focuses on downtime. Understanding both is crucial for designing effective backup and recovery strategies that align with business needs and risk tolerance.",
    examTip: "Remember RPO (Point) focuses on data loss, while RTO (Time) focuses on downtime; this distinction is frequently tested.",
