    blueprintArea: "ISC-II",
    topic: "Security Controls",
    subtopic: "Defense in Depth",
    difficulty: "medium",
    skillLevel: "Application",
    question: "Defense in depth is a security strategy that:",
    options: ["Prioritizes speed over security","Uses multiple layers of security controls","Focuses only on endpoint protection","Relies on a single strong perimeter firewall"],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Defense in depth: Multiple overlapping security layers (physical, network, host, application, data). If one layer fails, others provide protection. Includes: firewalls, IDS/IPS, encryption, access controls, training, monitoring. No single point of failure.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Defense in depth prioritizes security by using multiple layers, even if it slightly impacts speed. Speed is not the primary concern.",
      1: "Why option B is CORRECT - Defense in depth employs multiple, overlapping security controls across various layers (physical, network, application, etc.) to protect assets. This layered approach ensures that if one control fails, others are in place to mitigate the risk.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - Focusing solely on endpoint protection is insufficient for a comprehensive security strategy. Defense in depth includes endpoint protection but also encompasses other layers like network and physical security.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - Relying solely on a single firewall creates a single point of failure. Defense in depth aims to eliminate single points of failure by implementing multiple security measures.",
    },
    educational: "Defense in depth is like an onion; it has many layers. Each layer provides a different type of security, and if an attacker gets through one layer, they still have to contend with the others. This strategy reduces the risk of a successful attack by making it more difficult for attackers to penetrate the entire system.",
    examTip: "When you see 'defense in depth,' think 'multiple layers' and 'no single point of failure'.",
    memoryAid: "Think of a castle: walls, moat, guards, and drawbridge – all working together for defense in depth.",
