    explanation: "Developers having ability to migrate their own changes to production is a critical segregation of duties violation. This creates opportunity for unauthorized changes without independent review. Emergency change procedures (with proper documentation and review) are an acceptable control.",
    whyWrong: {
      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Logging and tracking all changes is a good practice that promotes accountability and auditability, indicating strong change management.",
      1: "Why option B is WRONG - While not ideal, emergency changes bypassing normal procedures are acceptable if followed by thorough after-the-fact documentation and review to maintain control and accountability.",
      2: "Why option C is CORRECT - Developers migrating their own code to production violates segregation of duties. This allows developers to bypass independent review and potentially introduce unauthorized or malicious code, increasing the risk of errors and fraud.",
      3: "Why option D is WRONG - Requiring management approval before implementation is a key control activity, ensuring changes are aligned with business objectives and properly vetted.",
    },
    educational: "Segregation of duties is a fundamental internal control principle. It divides responsibilities among different individuals to prevent errors and fraud. In IT, this means separating development, testing, and production deployment to ensure independent oversight and prevent unauthorized changes.",
    examTip: "Always be on the lookout for segregation of duties violations, especially when dealing with IT controls; they are frequently tested.",
    memoryAid: "SOD: Separate, Oversee, Deter",
    reference: "Change Management Controls",
