      0: "Why option A is WRONG - Defining the scope of a penetration test solely by target systems is insufficient; it omits crucial elements like authorized techniques and rules of engagement, leading to potential legal or operational issues.",
      1: "Why option B is WRONG - Dates alone do not define the scope of a penetration test. While timing is a factor, the scope encompasses much more, including the systems to be tested and the methods to be used.",
      2: "Why option C is WRONG - Budget is a constraint on a penetration test, not a defining element of its scope. The scope outlines what will be tested and how, while the budget determines how much of that scope can be covered.",
