    difficulty: "medium",
    skillLevel: "Remembering and Understanding",
    question: "A company, SecureData Inc., processes highly sensitive customer financial information. Due to regulatory requirements and internal risk assessments, they need to determine the appropriate backup frequency and retention period for their transaction logs. They have a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 4 hours and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 1 hour. Which of the following backup strategies would best align with these objectives and generally accepted best practices?",
    options: ["Daily full backups with transaction log backups every 2 hours, retaining backups for 7 days.","Weekly full backups with daily differential backups and transaction log backups every 30 minutes, retaining backups for 30 days.","Monthly full backups with daily incremental backups and transaction log backups every 4 hours, retaining backups for 90 days.","Real-time replication to a secondary site with no additional transaction log backups, retaining historical data at the secondary site for 1 year."],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "Option B is the most appropriate. The RPO of 1 hour necessitates frequent transaction log backups (every 30 minutes ensures minimal data loss). Daily differential backups provide a balance between backup speed and restoration complexity compared to incremental backups. Retaining backups for 30 days allows for a reasonable recovery window. This strategy aligns with COBIT's focus on meeting stakeholder needs and regulatory requirements.",
