    question: "A regional bank, facing increasing cybersecurity threats, is reviewing its data backup and recovery strategy. The bank's core banking system processes all customer transactions and generates critical daily reports for regulatory compliance. An outage would significantly disrupt operations and could lead to substantial financial penalties. Senior management has mandated a maximum data loss of one hour and a maximum system downtime of four hours. Considering these requirements, which of the following strategies best balances cost and risk?\n",
    options: ["Implement a full data backup every 24 hours with offsite storage and a cold site for disaster recovery.","Implement a continuous data replication solution to a geographically separate hot site, with failover testing performed quarterly.","Implement differential backups every 4 hours with onsite storage and a warm site for disaster recovery.","Implement incremental backups every hour with onsite storage and a cold site for disaster recovery."],
    correctAnswer: 1,
    explanation: "A continuous data replication solution to a hot site best meets the RPO and RTO requirements. Continuous replication ensures minimal data loss (approaching zero), aligning with the one-hour maximum data loss. A hot site allows for rapid failover, minimizing downtime and aligning with the four-hour maximum downtime. Regular failover testing validates the effectiveness of the solution. This aligns with COBIT's focus on business continuity and risk management, NIST Cybersecurity Framework's ID.BE-4 (Business Continuity), and ISO 27001's A.17 (Information security aspects of business continuity management).",
