    question: "A regional bank, First Fidelity, experienced a major system outage at 2:00 PM on a Tuesday due to a hardware failure. Their data backup plan has a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 4 hours and a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 6 hours. The last successful data backup was completed at 10:00 AM on the same Tuesday. Assuming the recovery process begins immediately, what is the EARLIEST time the bank can realistically expect to have its systems fully restored and what is the MAXIMUM data loss the bank should expect, respectively?",
    options: ["8:00 PM Tuesday; 4 hours of data","8:00 PM Tuesday; 6 hours of data","4:00 PM Tuesday; 4 hours of data","4:00 PM Tuesday; 6 hours of data"],
    correctAnswer: 0,
    explanation: "The RTO is 6 hours, so starting the recovery at 2:00 PM, the systems should be restored by 8:00 PM. The RPO is 4 hours, meaning the maximum acceptable data loss is 4 hours. Since the last backup was at 10:00 AM and the failure was at 2:00 PM, the maximum data loss is 4 hours (2:00 PM - 10:00 AM = 4 hours). NIST Cybersecurity Framework (specifically Identify ID.BE-2, Backup and Recovery Improvement) and ISO 27001 emphasize the importance of defining and adhering to RPO and RTO.",
