    question: "A regional bank utilizes a third-party vendor for its core banking system. The vendor provides regular updates to the software. After a recent update, several users reported that a previously available report, used for daily cash reconciliation, is no longer functioning correctly. The IT security manager investigates and discovers that a key configuration setting related to report generation was unintentionally changed during the update process. Which of the following actions would have MOST effectively prevented this incident, according to best practices in configuration management?",
    options: ["Implementing a robust change management process that includes testing in a non-production environment before deploying updates to the production environment, and a rollback plan.","Enforcing strict password policies for all vendor personnel accessing the bank's systems, requiring multi-factor authentication.","Requiring the vendor to provide a Service Organization Control (SOC) 1 report annually, focusing on internal controls over financial reporting.","Conducting penetration testing of the core banking system on a quarterly basis to identify potential vulnerabilities."],
