    educational: "Multi-factor authentication (MFA) requires two or more independent factors to verify a user's identity. Common factors include something you know (password), something you have (token), and something you are (biometrics). Choosing the right MFA method depends on the risk assessment and security requirements.",
    examTip: "When evaluating MFA options, prioritize those that are resistant to common attack vectors like phishing and SMS interception. Look for options that are based on open standards and are regularly updated.",
    memoryAid: "Think of MFA as 'Something you KNOW, something you HAVE, something you ARE.' Evaluate each factor's strength and resistance to attacks.",
