    skillLevel: "Application",
    question: "A CPA firm, Smith & Jones, is implementing multi-factor authentication (MFA) for accessing client tax data. They are considering several MFA methods. Based on a recent risk assessment which identified that 30% of data breaches originate from phishing attacks targeting SMS-based MFA, and another 20% exploit vulnerabilities in password managers often used in conjunction with weaker MFA methods, which of the following MFA implementations would be MOST appropriate, balancing security and user convenience, while adhering to NIST SP 800-53 guidelines?",
    options: ["SMS-based one-time passwords (OTP) for all users, with a policy requiring complex passwords managed by a firm-approved password manager.","Authenticator app with push notifications for all users, combined with biometric authentication (fingerprint or facial recognition) on users' devices where available.","Knowledge-based authentication (KBA) questions (e.g., mother's maiden name) as a secondary factor, coupled with IP address whitelisting.","Hardware security keys (e.g., YubiKey) for partners and managers, and SMS-based OTP for all other staff."],
